definition.value: A mannosyl group derived from N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-mannose.

A mixture of semisynthetic avermectin derivatives comprising >=90% eprinomectin component B1a (R = CH3) and <=10% eprinomectin component B1b (R = H). It is used for the treatment of internal and external parasites in cattle.

An avermectin analogue that is avermectin A1a in which the methoxy group attached to the tetrahydrobenzofuranyl moiety is replaced by a hydroxy group and in which the hydroxy group at position 4 of the terminal 2,6-dideoxy-3-O-methyl-alpha-L-arabino-hyxopoyranosyl group is replaced by an acetamido group.
An avermectin analogue that is eprinomectin B1a in which the butan-2-yl substituent of the spiroketal moiety is replaced by an isopropyl group.
A macrolide whose structure is related to that of an avermectin.
An organic calcium salt that is the hemicalcium salt of zofenopril. A prodrug for zofenoprilat.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of zofenopril, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A proline derivative that is 4-(phenylsulfanyl)-L-proline in which the amine proton is replaced by a (2S)-2-methyl-3-sulfanylpropanoyl group. The active metabolite of zofenopril.
An organoammonium salt obtained by combining zofenoprilat with one molar equivalent of L-arginine.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of zofenoprilat, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 5-phosphate(3-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 1,2-dibutyryl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(1'D-myo-inositol-5'-phosphate); major species at pH 7.3.
A 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol(1-) that is the conjugate base of 1,2-dibutyryl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-1D-myo-inositol, obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group; major species at pH 7.3.
A sialotetraosylceramide having alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->3)-[alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->6)]-beta-D-GalNAc-(1->4)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-Glc as the sialotetraosyl component.
A sialotetraosylceramide having alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->3)-[alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->6)]-beta-D-GalNAc-(1->4)-[alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->3)]-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-Glc as the sialotetraosyl component.

A sialotetraosylceramide having alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->3)-[alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->6)]-beta-D-GalNAc-(1->4)-[alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->8)-alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->3)]-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-Glc as the sialotetraosyl component.
A hydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone that is 2-O-methylflaviolin in which the hydrogens at positions 3 and 6 are replaced by methyl and linalyl groups respectively.
A member of the class of naphthoquinones that is 2-O-methylflaviolin in which the hydrogen at position 3 is  replaced by a methyl group.
An alpha-amino-acid residue derived from S-methyl-L-cysteine.
A purinyl group that is 6-O-methyl guaninyl group with its point of attachment at position 9.
A carboxamidinium ion resulting from the protonation of both of the amidino groups of diminazene. The major species at pH 7.3.
An N-acetylglycinate salt resulting from the reaction of diminazene with 2 mol eq. of N-acetylglycine.
Any salt prepared using N-acetylglycine as the acid component.
An octadecenoic acid with a cis-double bond at position C-13.
An octadecenoate that is the conjugate base of (13Z)-octadecenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is 3,5,7-trihydroxy-4'-methoxy-8-prenylflavone in which the hydroxy group at position 3 has been converted into its alpha-L-rhamnopyranoside.
An alpha-amino-acid residue anion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of L-tyrosine-O-phosphate residue; major speices aqt pH 7.3.

An organic heterotricyclic compound that is 3a,4,8,9a-tetrahydro-2H-furo[3,2-g][2]benzopyran-2,9(3H)-dione that is substituted at positions 3, 6, and 9a by hexanoyl, (1E)-prop-1-en-1-yl and methyl groups, respectively (the 3S,3aR,9aR diastereoisomer). One of the azaphilonoid pigments in extracts of Monascus pilosus-fermented rice (red-mould rice), it is a potent inhibitor of carcinogenesis measured against chemical- or UV-initiated, phorbol-promoted mouse skin tumours.
A synthetic macrolide that is an analogue of the marine metabolite leucascandrolide A that exhibits comparable antiproliferative properties.

A zinc atom in which the nucleus contains 35 neutrons. It has a half-life of 244 days, decaying by emission of a positron (beta(+) decay), and is the most abundant and stable of the 25 known radioisotopes of zinc.
A trehalose mycolate compound consisting of two C58 mycolate groups attached to the 6- and 6'-positions of alpha,alpha'-trehalose. A mycobacterial cell wall glycolipid.

A chromanol that is 6-hydroxychromane which is substituted by a carboxy group at position 2 and by methyl groups at positions 2, 5, 7, and 8. A cell-permeable, water-soluble analogue of vitamin E, it is used as a standard for measuring the antioxidant capacity of complex mixtures.
A hydroperoxy fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 15(R)-HPETE, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A HPETE that is (5Z,8Z,11Z,13E,15R)-icosa-5,8,11,13-tetraenoic acid with the hydroperoxy group located at position 15 (the R-enantiomer).
A hydroperoxy fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 11(R)-HPETE, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A prostaglandin carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of prostaglandin G2, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A glycosylphosphatidylinositolethanolamine in which the nitrogen is substituted by a threonyl group.

A chromophore that is a linear tetrapyrrolic prosthetic group covalently attached to a large soluble protein phytochrome. Light absorption by the phytochrome chromophore triggers photoconversion between two spectrally distinct forms of the photoreceptor: Pr, the red light absorbing form, and Pfr, the far-red light absorbing form.
An anionic ganglioside that is the conjugate base of N-acetyl-alpha-neuraminosyl-(2->3)-D-galactosylceramide arising from deprotonation of the neuraminosyl carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A carboxylic ester resulting from the formal condensation of the alcoholic hydroxy group of (7Z)-14-hydroxy-10,13-dioxoheptadec-7-enoic acid with the free carboxy group of a peptidyl aspartate.
A phenyl acetate resulting from the formal condensation of the hydroxy group of 4-nitrophenol with the carboxy group of acetic acid.
A polyatomic cation consisting of a dodecyl group and three phenyl groups attached to a central phosphonium.

An anionic ganglioside that is the conjugate base of alpha-N-acetylneuraminosyl-(2->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->3)-N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl-(1->4)-[alpha-N acetylneuraminosyl-(2->3)]-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosyl-(1<->1')-ceramide arising from deprotonation of the neuraminosyl carboxy groups; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic bromide salt that containing equal numbers of dodecyl(triphenyl)phosphonium cations and bromide anions.
